ent/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/changelog/v1.2.2.0.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/03--scoring-system/02-dynamic-profiling.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/lib/profile-resolve.cjs\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/02--integration-scanning/03-command-dispatch.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/assets/agent-improvement/target_manifest.jsonc\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/changelog/v1.5.0.0.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/03--scoring-system/03-deterministic-scoring.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/lib/README.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/04--model-benchmark-mode/01-mode-switch.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/03--scoring-system/04-dimensional-progress.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/04--model-benchmark-mode/04-mode-records-and-gates.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/04--model-benchmark-mode/02-model-dispatcher.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/assets/agent-improvement/improvement_strategy.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/04--model-benchmark-mode/03-opt-in-5dim-scorer.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/assets/agent-improvement/improvement_charter.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/03--scoring-system/01-five-dimension-rubric.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/default.json\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/assets/agent-improvement/improvement_config_reference.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/changelog/v1.7.0.0.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/assets/agent-improvement/improvement_config.json\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/graph-metadata.json\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/shared/promote-candidate.cjs\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/shared/materialize-benchmark-fixtures.cjs\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/model-benchmark/scorer/lib/cache.cjs\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/model-benchmark/scorer/lib/README.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/tests/fixtures/low-sample-benchmark/README.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/model-benchmark/scorer/.gitignore\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/shared/improvement-journal.cjs\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/shared/mutation-coverage.cjs\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/assets/agent-improvement/target-profiles/.gitkeep\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/lib/promotion-gates.cjs\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/lib/mirror-sync-verify.cjs\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/lib/typed-errors.cjs\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/tests/fixtures/low-sample-benchmark/improvement_config.json\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/tests/fixtures/low-sample-benchmark/improvement-journal.jsonl\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/tests/fixtures/low-sample-benchmark/candidate-lineage.json\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/tests/fixtures/low-sample-benchmark/mutation-coverage.json\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/tests/fixtures/low-sample-benchmark/trade-off-trajectory.json\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/tests/fixtures/low-sample-benchmark/agent-improvement-state.jsonl\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/tests/fixtures/low-sample-benchmark/benchmark-results.json\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-fixtures/fixture-baseline.json\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-fixtures/fixture-improved.json\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-fixtures/fixture-edge.json\n\n(Results are truncated: showing first 100 results. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"count":100,"truncated":true},"title":"","time":{"start":1780204951595,"end":1780204951624}},"id":"prt_e7c7bd6f2001iVbFWrPGDrrBqC","sessionID":"ses_183846c24ffe2Qtb7Q7eSJvXlI","messageID":"msg_e7c7bc1dd001O0Vzm4smrnw4WO"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780204951868,"sessionID":"ses_183846c24ffe2Qtb7Q7eSJvXlI","part":{"id":"prt_e7c7bd93b001gbczy3l4Q1ndbj","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"024519e087ccb85b800557a2a3e443843654f7ad","messageID":"msg_e7c7bc1dd001O0Vzm4smrnw4WO","sessionID":"ses_183846c24ffe2Qtb7Q7eSJvXlI","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":34863,"input":9715,"output":211,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":1191,"read":23746}},"cost":0.008206785}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780204956176,"sessionID":"ses_183846c24ffe2Qtb7Q7eSJvXlI","part":{"id":"prt_e7c7bea090014JbqiR51t8RU9a","messageID":"msg_e7c7bda26001QLqUg47WFBhmYt","sessionID":"ses_183846c24ffe2Qtb7Q7eSJvXlI","snapshot":"9376f40411e70984ae041ccbb20026dc4ed59640","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780204959724,"sessionID":"ses_183846c24ffe2Qtb7Q7eSJvXlI","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_ycc2i6htwgri_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/SKILL.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: deep-improvement\n3: description: \"Evaluator-first bounded agent improvement: 5-dim scoring, dynamic profiling, packet-local candidates, guarded promotion.\"\n4: allowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Glob, Grep]\n5: version: 1.9.0.0\n6: triggers:\n7:   - deep-improvement\n8:   - agent improvement loop\n9:   - bounded agent improvement\n10:   - 5-dimension scoring\n11:   - integration scanner\n12:   - dynamic profiling\n13:   - model-benchmark mode\n14:   - benchmark a model or prompt framework\n15: ---\n16: \n17: <!-- Keywords: deep-improvement, deep-improvement, agent-improvement, benchmark-harness, score-candidate, promote-candidate, rollback-candidate -->\n18: \n19: # Recursive Agent: Evaluator-First Improvement Orchestrator\n20: \n21: Evaluator-first workflow for testing whether a bounded agent surface can be improved without immediately mutating the source of truth. It combines packet-local candidates, deterministic scoring, repeatable benchmarks, and explicit promotion or rollback gates.\n22: \n23: ---\n24: \n25: ## 1. WHEN TO USE\n26: \n27: ### Three Co-Equal Lanes\n28: \n29: This skill supports three co-equal use-case lanes that share the same candidate, dispatcher, and scorer seams:\n30: \n31: | Lane | Pick when | Command |\n32: | --- | --- | --- |\n33: | **Lane A: Agent-Improvement** | You want to improve a bounded agent `.md` file | `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` |\n34: | **Lane B: Model-Benchmark** | You want to benchmark a model or prompt framework | `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` |\n35: | **Lane C: Skill-Benchmark** | You want to diagnose a skill's real-world routing, discovery, efficiency, and usefulness | `/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop` |\n36: \n37: Lane A is detailed in §3 (Runtime Initialization, Proposal and Evaluation, Promotion and Recovery). Lane B is detailed in §4. Lane C (skill-benchmark) is documented in `references/skill-benchmark/` (operator guide, scoring contract, scenario authoring) and run via `loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark`. All three lanes run the same loop shape and keep the agent-improvement path byte-identical when no mode flag is set.\n38: \n39: ### Activation Triggers\n40: \n41: Use this skill when:\n42: - You want to test whether an agent prompt or instruction surface can be improved (Lane A)\n43: - You want to benchmark a model or prompt framework against repeatable fixtures (Lane B)\n44: - You want to diagnose whether a skill is well-routed, discoverable, efficient, and useful in practice (Lane C)\n45: - The mutation boundary is explicit and narrow\n46: - You need packet-local evidence instead of ad hoc prompt tweaking\n47: - You need target-specific benchmark or scoring rules before any canonical mutation\n48: - Promotion must stay gated behind independent evidence plus operator approval\n49: \n50: ### Primary Use Cases\n51: \n52: #### Bounded Agent Improvement\n53: \n54: Use this skill to set up a proposal-first loop for any bounded agent file, write packet-local candidates, and record append-only evidence.\n55: \n56: #### Benchmark-Backed Evaluation\n57: \n58: Use this skill when candidate quality must be judged by produced artifacts and repeatability reports, not just by how a prompt file reads in isolation.\n59: \n60: #### Promotion and Rollback Verification\n61: \n62: Use this skill when you need to prove that guarded promotion, validation, rollback, and post-rollback comparison all work end to end without leaving hidden drift behind.\n63: \n64: #### Model and Prompt Benchmarking\n65: \n66: Use Lane B (model-benchmark) when the thing under test is a model or prompt framework rather than an agent definition. It runs the same loop shape against a benchmark profile and scores produced outputs, sharing the candidate, dispatcher, and scorer seams with the agent-improvement path. See §4 below.\n67: \n68: #### Skill Benchmarking\n69: \n70: Use Lane C (skill-benchmark) when the thing under test is a *skill* — to measure whether AIs actually get routed to it, discover its references/assets unprompted, use it efficiently, and benefit from it. It emits a ranked, remediable Skill Benchmark Report and is diagnostic by default (it does not mutate the target skill). See `references/skill-benchmark/operator_guide.md`.\n71: \n72: ### When NOT to Use\n73: \n74: Do not use this skill for:\n75: - Open-ended prompt rewrites across multiple agent families at once\n76: - Direct canonical edits without a packet-local candidate and evaluator evidence\n77: - Broad runtime-mirror synchronization work presented as benchmark truth\n78: - General packet planning that belongs in `/speckit:plan` or implementation that does not need an improvement loop\n79: \n80: ---\n81: \n82: ## 2. SMART ROUTING\n83: \n84: \n85: ### Resource Domains\n86: \n87: The router discovers markdown resources recursively from `references/` and `assets/`, then applies intent scoring so only the guidance that matches the current task is loaded.\n88: \n89: - `references/` for operator workflows, evaluator policy, promotion or rollback rules, target onboarding, and quick-reference guidance\n90: - `assets/` for reusable runtime templates such as the charter and strategy markdown files\n91: - `scripts/` for deterministic benchmark, scoring, reduction, promotion, rollback, and drift-check helpers\n92: \n93: **Lane awareness**: resources are organized by lane. `references/agent-improvement/` + `assets/agent-improvement/` carry Lane A guidance, `references/model-benchmark/` + `assets/model-benchmark/` carry Lane B guidance, and `references/skill-benchmark/` + `assets/skill-benchmark/` carry Lane C guidance. `RESOURCE_MAP` routes the `MODEL_BENCHMARK` and `SKILL_BENCHMARK` intents to their lane references, and `RUNTIME_ASSETS` loads each lane's profile only when its intent is selected. The `ALWAYS` and shared `references/shared/` resources apply to all three lanes.\n94: \n95: ### Resource Loading Levels\n96: \n97: | Level | When to Load | Resources |\n98: | --- | --- | --- |\n99: | ALWAYS | Every skill invocation | `references/shared/quick_reference.md` |\n100: | CONDITIONAL | If intent signals match | Workflow, policy, or onboarding references |\n101: | ON_DEMAND | Only on explicit request or full setup | Markdown runtime templates in `assets/` |\n102: \n103: ### Smart Router Pseudocode\n104: \n105: The authoritative routing logic for scoped markdown loading and explicit runtime-asset loading.\n106: \n107: - Pattern 1: Runtime Discovery - `discover_markdown_resources()` recursively scans `references/` and `assets/`.\n108: - Pattern 2: Existence-Check Before Load - `load_if_available()` uses `_guard_in_skill()`, `inventory`, and `seen`.\n109: - Pattern 3: Extensible Routing Key - quick-reference, loop, evaluation, promotion, target onboarding, integration, and setup intents route resources.\n110: - Pattern 4: Multi-Tier Graceful Fallback - `UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST` asks for target/action/gate disambiguation and missing intent routes return a \"no knowledge base\" notice.\n111: \n112: ```python\n113: from pathlib import Path\n114: \n115: SKILL_ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent\n116: RESOURCE_BASES = (SKILL_ROOT / \"references\", SKILL_ROOT / \"assets\")\n117: DEFAULT_RESOURCE = \"references/shared/quick_reference.md\"\n118: \n119: INTENT_SIGNALS = {\n120:     \"QUICK_REFERENCE\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"quick reference\", \"short reminder\", \"command example\"]},\n121:     \"LOOP_EXECUTION\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"run loop\", \"proposal\", \"candidate\", \"score candidate\", \"benchmark\"]},\n122:     \"EVALUATION_POLICY\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"evaluator\", \"rubric\", \"contract\", \"repeatability\", \"no-go\"]},\n123:     \"PROMOTION_OPERATIONS\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"promote\", \"rollback\", \"mirror drift\", \"approval gate\"]},\n124:     \"TARGET_ONBOARDING\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"new target\", \"target profile\", \"onboarding\", \"second target\"]},\n125:     \"INTEGRATION_SCAN\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"integration\", \"scan surfaces\", \"mirror sync\", \"dynamic profile\", \"5-dimension\"]},\n126:     \"MODEL_BENCHMARK\": {\"weight\": 5, \"keywords\": [\"benchmark a model\", \"benchmark a prompt framework\", \"optimize a model\", \"model-benchmark\", \"model benchmark\"]},\n127:     \"SKILL_BENCHMARK\": {\"weight\": 5, \"keywords\": [\"benchmark a skill\", \"skill benchmark\", \"skill routing\", \"unprompted discovery\", \"routing accuracy\", \"skill-benchmark\"]},\n128:     \"FULL_SETUP\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"full setup\", \"initialize runtime\", \"charter\", \"strategy\"]},\n129: }\n130: \n131: RESOURCE_MAP = {\n132:     \"QUICK_REFERENCE\": [\"references/shared/quick_reference.md\"],\n133:     \"LOOP_EXECUTION\": [\"references/shared/loop_protocol.md\", \"references/model-benchmark/benchmark_operator_guide.md\"],\n134:     \"EVALUATION_POLICY\": [\"references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md\", \"references/shared/promotion_rules.md\"],\n135:     \"PROMOTION_OPERATIONS\": [\"references/shared/rollback_runbook.md\", \"references/agent-improvement/mirror_drift_policy.md\", \"references/shared/promotion_rules.md\"],\n136:     \"TARGET_ONBOARDING\": [\"references/agent-improvement/target_onboarding.md\"],\n137:     \"INTEGRATION_SCAN\": [\"references/agent-improvement/integration_scanning.md\", \"references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md\"],\n138:     \"MODEL_BENCHMARK\": [\"references/model-benchmark/benchmark_operator_guide.md\", \"references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md\"],\n139:     \"SKILL_BENCHMARK\": [\"references/skill-benchmark/operator_guide.md\", \"references/skill-benchmark/scoring_contract.md\", \"references/skill-benchmark/scenario_authoring.md\"],\n140:     \"FULL_SETUP\": [\"assets/agent-improvement/improvement_charter.md\", \"assets/agent-improvement/improvement_strategy.md\"],\n141: }\n142: \n143: RUNTIME_ASSETS = {\n144:     \"ALWAYS\": [\"assets/agent-improvement/improvement_config.json\", \"assets/agent-improvement/target_manifest.jsonc\"],\n145:     \"MODEL_BENCHMARK\": [\"assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/default.json\"],\n146:     \"SKILL_BENCHMARK\": [\"assets/skill-benchmark/default_profile.json\"],\n147: }\n148: \n149: ON_DEMAND_KEYWORDS = [\"target profile\", \"score candidate\", \"proposal loop\", \"benchmark\", \"promotion gate\", \"mirror drift\"]\n150: \n151: def _task_text(task) -> str:\n152:     return \" \".join([\n153:         str(getattr(task, \"text\", \"\")),\n154:         str(getattr(task, \"query\", \"\")),\n155:         \" \".join(getattr(task, \"keywords\", []) or []),\n156:     ]).lower()\n157: \n158: UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST = [\"Confirm target path\", \"Confirm proposal vs scoring vs promotion\", \"Confirm packet-local evidence path\"]\n159: \n160: def _guard_in_skill(relative_path: str) -> str:\n161:     resolved = (SKILL_ROOT / relative_path).resolve()\n162:     resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT)\n163:     if resolved.suffix.lower() != \".md\":\n164:         raise ValueError(f\"Only markdown resources are routed here: {relative_path}\")\n165:     return resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix()\n166: \n167: def discover_markdown_resources() -> set[str]:\n168:     docs = []\n169:     for base in RESOURCE_BASES:\n170:         if base.exists():\n171:             docs.extend(p for p in base.rglob(\"*.md\") if p.is_file())\n172:     return {doc.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix() for doc in docs}\n173: \n174: def score_intents(task) -> dict[str, float]:\n175:     text = _task_text(task)\n176:     scores = {intent: 0.0 for intent in INTENT_SIGNALS}\n177:     for intent, cfg in INTENT_SIGNALS.items():\n178:         for keyword in cfg[\"keywords\"]:\n179:             if keyword in text:\n180:                 scores[intent] += cfg[\"weight\"]\n181:     return scores\n182: \n183: def select_intents(scores: dict[str, float], ambiguity_delta: float = 1.0, max_intents: int = 2) -> list[str]:\n184:     ranked = sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True)\n185:     if not ranked or ranked[0][1] <= 0:\n186:         return [\"QUICK_REFERENCE\"]\n187:     selected = [ranked[0][0]]\n188:     if len(ranked) > 1 and ranked[1][1] > 0 and (ranked[0][1] - ranked[1][1]) <= ambiguity_delta:\n189:         selected.append(ranked[1][0])\n190:     return selected[:max_intents]\n191: \n192: def route_recursive_agent_resources(task):\n193:     inventory = discover_markdown_resources()\n194:     intents = select_intents(score_intents(task))\n195:     loaded = []\n196:     seen = set()\n197: \n198:     def load_if_available(relative_path: str) -> None:\n199:         guarded = _guard_in_skill(relative_path)\n200:         if guarded in inventory and guarded not in seen:\n201:             load(guarded)\n202:             loaded.append(guarded)\n203:             seen.add(guarded)\n204: \n205:     load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\n206:     for intent in intents:\n207:         for relative_path in RESOURCE_MAP.get(intent, []):\n208:             load_if_available(relative_path)\n209: \n210:     text = _task_text(task)\n211:     if any(keyword in text for keyword in ON_DEMAND_KEYWORDS):\n212:         for paths in RESOURCE_MAP.values():\n213:             for relative_path in paths:\n214:                 load_if_available(relative_path)\n215: \n216:     runtime_assets = list(RUNTIME_ASSETS[\"ALWAYS\"])\n217:     if \"MODEL_BENCHMARK\" in intents:\n218:         runtime_assets.extend(RUNTIME_ASSETS.get(\"MODEL_BENCHMARK\", []))\n219: \n220:     if not loaded:\n221:         load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\n222:     return {\"intents\": intents, \"resources\": loaded, \"runtime_assets\": runtime_assets}\n223: ```\n224: \n225: ---\n226: \n227: ## 3. LANE A: AGENT-IMPROVEMENT\n228: \n229: Lane A improves a bounded agent `.md` file. Command: `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`. It runs the proposal-first loop in three modes (initialization, proposal and evaluation, promotion and recovery) and scores candidates with dynamic-mode 5-dimension scoring.\n230: \n231: ### Mode 1: Runtime Initialization\n232: \n233: 1. Confirm the spec folder, target path, execution mode, and active target profile.\n234: 2. Create `{spec_folder}/improvement/` plus the packet-local `candidates/`, `benchmark-runs/`, and `archive/` directories when needed.\n235: 3. Copy in the runtime config, charter, strategy, and boundary templates.\n236: 4. Record baseline state in the append-only ledger before the first candidate run.\n237: \n238: ### Mode 2: Proposal and Evaluation\n239: \n240: 1. Read the charter, boundary file, target profile, and canonical target surface.\n241: 2. Run `scripts/agent-improvement/scan-integration.cjs` to discover all surfaces the target agent touches.\n242: 3. Write exactly one bounded candidate under the packet-local `candidates/` directory.\n243: 4. Run `scripts/agent-improvement/score-candidate.cjs` to evaluate the candidate via dynamic-mode 5-dimension scoring (the sole supported path).\n244: 5. Run `scripts/model-benchmark/run-benchmark.cjs` to measure produced outputs against the active fixture set.\n245: 6. Append score and benchmark results to the packet-local ledger.\n246: 7. Run `scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs` to refresh the dashboard and experiment registry.\n247: \n248: ### Mode 2A: Stress-Test Failure Paths Before Promotion Claims\n249: \n250: For changes that alter agent discipline, run at least one same-task A/B stress scenario before recommending promotion:\n251: \n252: 1. Call A: a generic improvement attempt against an isolated sandbox copy of the target.\n253: 2. Reset the sandbox to its baseline copy.\n254: 3. Call B: the disciplined `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` path against the identical prompt and files.\n255: 4. Judge only grep/file/diff/exit-code signals: helper invocation, packet-local candidate boundary, no canonical or mirror mutation before promotion, benchmark journal boundary, legal-stop gate keys, and stop-reason correctness.\n256: \n257: Do not treat `Read(SKILL.md)` or `skill(deep-improvement)` as evidence that this protocol executed.\n258: \n259: ### 5-Dimension Evaluation Framework\n260: \n261: Dynamic mode is the only scoring path. Scoring evaluates five dimensions:\n262: \n263: | Dimension | Weight | What It Measures |\n264: | --- | --- | --- |\n265: | Structural Integrity | 0.20 | Agent template compliance (required sections present) |\n266: | Rule Coherence | 0.25 | ALWAYS/NEVER rules align with workflow steps |\n267: | Integration Consistency | 0.25 | Mirrors in sync, commands reference agent, skills reference agent |\n268: | Output Quality | 0.15 | Output verification items present, no placeholder content |\n269: | System Fitness | 0.15 | Permission alignment, resource references valid, frontmatter complete |\n270: \n271: Profiles are generated on the fly from any agent file via `scripts/agent-improvement/generate-profile.cjs`. No static profiles are shipped. Every target is evaluated against its own derived structure and rules.\n272: \n273: ### Mode 3: Promotion and Recovery\n274: \n275: 1. Promote only when prompt scoring, benchmark status, repeatability, boundary, and approval gates all pass.\n276: 2. Use `scripts/shared/promote-candidate.cjs` for guarded canonical mutation.\n277: 3. Use `scripts/agent-improvement/rollback-candidate.cjs` plus direct comparison evidence when the canonical target must be restored.\n278: 4. Treat mirror drift as downstream packaging work and review it separately with `scripts/agent-improvement/check-mirror-drift.cjs`.\n279: \n280: ---\n281: \n282: ## 4. LANE B: MODEL-BENCHMARK\n283: \n284: Lane B benchmarks a model or prompt framework instead of mutating an agent file. Command: `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop`. Runtime entry is `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs --mode=model-benchmark`. It reuses the three pluggable seams (candidate-source, dispatcher, scorer) and keeps the default agent-improvement path byte-identical when no mode flag is set.\n285: \n286: 1. **Entry point**: `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs` resolves the mode. `--mode=agent-improvement` (or no flag) routes to `scripts/agent-improvement/score-candidate.cjs`. `--mode=model-benchmark` runs `scripts/shared/materialize-benchmark-fixtures.cjs` then `scripts/model-benchmark/run-benchmark.cjs`. An unknown mode warns and falls back to agent-improvement.\n287: 2. **Dispatcher**: `scripts/model-benchmark/dispatch-model.cjs` is the model-agnostic dispatcher (executor-routing map across cli-opencode, cli-claude-code, cli-codex, cli-gemini, cli-devin). It is loaded only on the model-benchmark path, never in agent-improvement mode.\n288: 3. **Scorer selection**: `run-benchmark.cjs --scorer pattern` (default) uses the heading/pattern matcher. `--scorer 5dim` routes materialized outputs through `scripts/model-benchmark/scorer/score-model-variant.cjs`, the ported 120/003 five-dimension scorer (deterministic checks plus a pluggable grader). `--grader noop` (default) stays deterministic with no model dispatch. `--grader mock` or `--grader llm` select the stub or real grader.\n289: 4. **Mode-aware records and promotion path**: every state record carries `mode: agent-improvement` or `mode: model-benchmark`, and benchmark reports carry `scoringMethod: pattern|5dim`, so the reducer (`reduce-state.cjs`) and downstream consumers can attribute results per lane. Record-level mode metadata lives in the reducer, NOT in the promoter. Lane A promotes a scored candidate through the agent-scored gates in `promote-candidate.cjs`. Lane B promotes from the benchmark report: pass `promote-candidate.cjs --benchmark-report <report.json>`, and when the report status is `benchmark-complete` with a passing benchmark recommendation, the benchmark-report path drives promotion and bypasses the agent-scored-file requirement. The promoter is NOT otherwise lane-branching beyond this benchmark-report path, both lanes share the same single canonical-target guard, archive, and runtime-mirror sync.\n290: 5. **Hardening env gates**: set `DEEP_AGENT_ALLOW_CRITERIA_EXEC=0` to refuse criteria-driven shell execution in the 5-dim scorer. When the gate is off, BOTH criteria-exec paths are refused: the deterministic-criterion `execSync` in `score-model-variant.cjs` AND the bundle-gate Layer-3 acceptance-command `execSync` in `bundle-gate.cjs`. Set `DEEP_AGENT_GRADER_CACHE_RAW=0` to redact raw grader output from the on-disk cache. Both default to the permissive value for backward-compat. **Trusted-author default rationale (DOCUMENT-ACCEPT)**: criteria commands originate only from benchmark profiles authored by the operator running the loop, and the deterministic criterion runs in the same trust domain as the loop itself, so the default-on behavior is an intended trusted-author boundary rather than an untrusted-input risk. A shipped backward-compat test asserts the criterion runs by default, so flipping the default would be a behavior change with test impact, not a silent hardening. Hardened or shared-runner deployments set `DEEP_AGENT_ALLOW_CRITERIA_EXEC=0` to fail closed, and `DEEP_AGENT_GRADER_CACHE_RAW=0` to redact cached grader output.\n291: \n292: ---\n293: \n294: ## 5. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n295: \n296: - The loop stays proposal-first unless an explicit guarded promotion path is requested\n297: - Benchmark evidence, prompt scoring, and mirror-sync evidence remain separate\n298: - Reducer outputs make the best-known state, rejected runs, infrastructure failures, and stop conditions easy to review\n299: - Operators can onboard a bounded target without weakening boundary or evaluator guardrails\n300: \n301: ---\n302: \n303: ## 6. MULTI-ITER METHODOLOGY\n304: \n305: For multi-iter evaluation sweeps, a mixed-executor split plus an adjudication pass gives better breadth, better synthesis, and less noise than a single-executor run.\n306: \n307: - **Mixed-executor 8+2 split**: run breadth iterations on cli-devin SWE-1.6 and synthesis iterations on cli-codex gpt-5.5. For a 10-iter sweep, that is iters 1-8 breadth and iters 9-10 synthesis.\n308: - **Adjudication iter**: insert a false-positive filter pass before the synthesis iterations (typically the iter-7 mark) so only confirmed findings carry forward. In validation this delivers a 90%+ false-positive reduction, with one pass dropping 9 false-positive and 4 outdated items to take a 20-item queue down to 7.\n309: \n310: See `references/model-benchmark/mixed_executor_methodology.md` for the split mechanics, adjudication details, and the full validation evidence.\n311: \n312: ---\n313: \n314: ## 7. RUNTIME TRUTH CONTRACTS\n315: \n316: ### Stop-Reason Taxonomy\n317: \n318: Every improvement session termination MUST produce both a `stopReason` (why) and a `sessionOutcome` (what happened).\n319: \n320: **stopReason** (WHY the session ended):\n321: \n322: | Reason | Trigger Condition |\n323: | --- | --- |\n324: | `converged` | All legal-stop gate bundles pass and dimension trajectory is stable |\n325: | `maxIterationsReached` | Iteration counter equals `maxIterations` config |\n326: | `blockedStop` | One or more legal-stop gate bundles fail when convergence math would otherwise trigger stop |\n327: | `manualStop` | Operator cancels the session |\n328: | `error` | Infra failure, script crash, or unrecoverable condition |\n329: | `stuckRecovery` | Session detected stuck state and exhausted recovery options |\n330: \n331: **sessionOutcome** (WHAT happened to the candidate):\n332: \n333: | Outcome | When Used |\n334: | --- | --- |\n335: | `keptBaseline` | Baseline was retained because candidate did not improve |\n336: | `promoted` | Candidate was promoted to canonical target |\n337: | `rolledBack` | Promoted candidate was rolled back to prior state |\n338: | `advisoryOnly` | Session completed for assessment only; no mutation attempted |\n339: \n340: ### Audit Journal Protocol\n341: \n342: All journal emission is orchestrator-only (ADR-001). The journal (`improvement-journal.jsonl`) is an append-only JSONL file capturing lifecycle events. Separate from the existing `agent-improvement-state.jsonl` which tracks proposal/evaluation data.\n343: \n344: **Script**: `scripts/shared/improvement-journal.cjs`\n345: \n346: Event types: `session_start`, `session_initialized`, `integration_scanned`, `candidate_generated`, `candidate_scored`, `benchmark_completed`, `gate_evaluation`, `legal_stop_evaluated`, `blocked_stop`, `promotion_attempt`, `promotion_result`, `rollback`, `rollback_result`, `trade_off_detected`, `mutation_proposed`, `mutation_outcome`, `session_ended`, `session_end`\n347: \n348: ### Static Benchmark Assets\n349: \n350: The reusable benchmark contract ships with the skill, not with each spec packet:\n351: \n352: - Profile: `assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/default.json`\n353: - Fixtures: `assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-fixtures/*.json`\n354: - Materializer: `scripts/shared/materialize-benchmark-fixtures.cjs`\n355: - Runner: `scripts/model-benchmark/run-benchmark.cjs`\n356: \n357: The command workflow first materializes static fixture JSON into packet-local markdown under `{spec_folder}/improvement/benchmark-outputs/{fixture.id}.md`, then runs `run-benchmark.cjs --profile .opencode/skills/deep-improvement/assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/default.json --outputs-dir {spec_folder}/improvement/benchmark-outputs`. The runner writes `{spec_folder}/improvement/benchmark-outputs/report.json` with `status:\"benchmark-complete\"` and appends a `benchmark_run` row to `{spec_folder}/improvement/agent-improvement-state.jsonl`.\n358: \n359: `benchmark_completed` may be emitted only after `benchmark-outputs/report.json` exists. Repeatability output from `benchmark-stability.cjs` is separate evidence and does not by itself prove benchmark completion.\n360: \n361: ### Legal-Stop Gate Bundles\n362: \n363: A session may NOT claim `converged` unless all five gate bundles pass: `contractGate`, `behaviorGate`, `integrationGate`, `evidenceGate`, and `improvementGate`. The orchestrator emits `legal_stop_evaluated` with nested `details.gateResults` before any `session_end`. Failures emit `blocked_stop` with `failedGates[]` and `stopReason:\"blockedStop\"`.\n364: \n365: ### Resume/Continuation Semantics (current release)\n366: \n367: Sessions support a single lineage mode today: `new`. Every invocation of the `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` workflow starts a fresh session with a new session id and generation 1. Multi-generation lineage modes (`resume`, `restart`, `fork`, `completed-continue`) were described in earlier drafts but have no shipped runtime wiring in the deep-improvement workflow, reducer, or journal consumer.\n368: \n369: Operators who want to continue evaluating an agent after a prior session SHOULD archive the prior session folder (e.g. move `improve/` to `improve_archive/{timestamp}/`) and re-invoke the command, which starts a new `new`-mode session. The reducer treats each session independently and does not carry ancestry across sessions.\n370: \n371: If the long-form lineage feature is implemented later, it will arrive with first-class event emission in `deep_start-agent-improvement-loop_{auto,confirm}.yaml`, reducer ancestry handling in `deep-improvement/scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs`, and replay fixtures. Until then, treat every session as a standalone evaluation.\n372: \n373: ### Mutation Coverage Graph\n374: \n375: **Script**: `scripts/shared/mutation-coverage.cjs`\n376: \n377: Tracks explored dimensions, tried mutation types per dimension, and exhausted mutation sets using `loop_type: \"improvement\"` namespace isolation (ADR-002). The orchestrator skips mutation types already in the exhausted log.\n378: \n379: #### Mutation Signature Dedup\n380: \n381: Each mutation entry in `mutation-coverage.json` carries a `signature` field computed as:\n382: \n383: ```text\n384: signature = sha256(dimension + \"\\u001f\" + mutationType + \"\\u001f\" + targetSection + \"\\u001f\" + normalizedBody64)\n385: ```\n386: \n387: Where `normalizedBody64` = whitespace-collapsed, lowercased, first 64 characters of the mutation body.\n388: \n389: **Dedup behavior:**\n390: - Before proposing a new mutation, `isSignatureSeen()` scans existing `mutations[]` and `exhausted[]` arrays\n391: - If the signature matches, the candidate is skipped with `reason: \"EXHAUSTED-FROM: iter-NNN\"` recorded in `exhausted[]`\n392: - The `EXHAUSTED-FROM` format references the iteration where the original mutation was tried\n393: \n394: **Bypass:**\n395: ```bash\n396: export DEEP_AGENT_IMPROVEMENT_SKIP_DEDUP=1  # Force re-evaluation of previously seen signatures\n397: ```\n398: When set, `isSignatureSeen()` always returns `{ seen: false }`. Every mutation is considered fresh.\n399: \n400: **Backward compatibility:** Legacy `mutation-coverage.json` entries without `signature` field fall back to the existing `dimension::mutationType` dedup in the reducer. No migration required.\n401: \n402: **Authoritative storage:** `mutation-coverage.json` `mutations[]` array. `signature` is written by `recordMutation()` and read by `isSignatureSeen()` and `reduce-state.cjs`.\n403: \n404: ### Dimension Trajectory\n405: \n406: Trajectory data records per-iteration dimension scores. Two distinct convergence signals run side by side and must not be conflated. `mutation-coverage.cjs` `checkConvergenceEligibility()` marks a profile convergence-eligible when it has at least 3 data points and every dimension delta across the last 3 points is within `DEFAULT_STABILITY_DELTA` (+/-2), a tolerance band. Separately, `reduce-state.cjs` `stopOnDimensionPlateau` fires the plateau stop only when a dimension's last 3 scores are identical (exact-repeat). The +/-2 trajectory eligibility and the exact-repeat plateau stop are different checks.\n407: \n408: Stop-condition counters (`maxConsecutiveTies`, `maxInfraFailuresPerProfile`, `maxWeakBenchmarkRunsPerProfile`) default to disabled, with no cap, unless the runtime config sets them. Only configured counters can trigger `blockedStop`.\n409: \n410: ### Trade-Off Detection\n411: \n412: **Script**: `scripts/agent-improvement/trade-off-detector.cjs`\n413: \n414: Detects Pareto trade-offs: flags when improvement > +3 in one dimension causes regression < -3 in hard dimensions (structural, integration, systemFitness) or < -5 in soft dimensions (ruleCoherence, outputQuality). Blocks promotion for Pareto-dominated candidates.\n415: \n416: ### Parallel Candidate Waves (Optional)\n417: \n418: **Script**: `scripts/agent-improvement/candidate-lineage.cjs`\n419: \n420: Disabled by default (`parallelWaves.enabled: false` in config, ADR-004). When enabled, spawns 2-3 candidates with different mutation strategies. Activation requires: exploration-breadth score above threshold, 3+ unresolved mutation families, and 2 consecutive tie/plateau iterations.\n421: \n422: ### Weight Optimizer (Advisory Only)\n423: \n424: **Script**: `scripts/agent-improvement/benchmark-stability.cjs`\n425: \n426: Reads historical session data and emits a weight-recommendation report. Recommendations do NOT auto-apply (ADR-005). Requires minimum session count threshold before producing recommendations.\n427: \n428: ---\n429: \n430: ### Journal Wiring Contract\n431: \n432: Journal emission is orchestrator-only. The target agent being evaluated never writes journal rows directly. Only the visible YAML workflow or an operator-side wrapper invokes `scripts/shared/improvement-journal.cjs`.\n433: \n434: The CLI contract is:\n435: \n436: ```bash\n437: node .opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/shared/improvement-journal.cjs --emit <eventType> --journal <journal_path> --details '<json>'\n438: ```\n439: \n440: The helper validates event type plus `session_end` or `session_ended` details, and the CLI entrypoint stores boundary context under `details`. Top-level `iteration` and `candidateId` fields are available only through the JS API, not through the CLI wrapper used by the YAML workflows.\n441: \n442: ### Boundary Points\n443: \n444: Journal boundaries are `session_start` after baseline setup, per-iteration candidate/scoring/gate events, and `session_end` after synthesis or terminal stop. Required details include session id, target, iteration/candidate paths, scores, stop reason, session outcome, and total iterations.\n445: \n446: ### Frozen Helper Enums\n447: \n448: `improvement-journal.cjs` currently exports and validates the following enums:\n449: \n450: - `STOP_REASONS`: `converged`, `maxIterationsReached`, `blockedStop`, `manualStop`, `error`, `stuckRecovery`\n451: - `SESSION_OUTCOMES`: `keptBaseline`, `promoted`, `rolledBack`, `advisoryOnly`\n452: \n453: Keep session-end emissions aligned to those helper-owned values until the helper contract itself changes. Labels such as `convergedImprovement`, `plateau`, `benchmarkPlateau`, `rejected`, `deferred`, `blocked`, or `errored` are not accepted by the current CLI validator. Plateau detection is a reducer/stop-rule condition. It must reconcile to one of the canonical stop reasons above when emitted as `details.stopReason`.\n454: \n455: ### Orchestrator Ownership\n456: \n457: - Auto mode emits `session_start` after `step_record_baseline`, then emits `candidate_generated`, `candidate_scored`, and `gate_evaluation` inside each loop iteration, and finally emits `session_end` after synthesis.\n458: - Confirm mode mirrors the same boundaries, with `gate_evaluation` emitted after the operator-facing approval gate is resolved.\n459: - Operators invoking the helper manually must use the same boundary order so replay and reducer consumers see a consistent journal shape.\n460: \n461: ### Reducer Consumer Side\n462: \n463: The reducer is the consumer for replay artifacts on refresh. Every `scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs` pass now attempts to read:\n464: \n465: - `improvement-journal.jsonl`\n466: - `candidate-lineage.json`\n467: - `mutation-coverage.json`\n468: \n469: These inputs remain optional. Missing files do not fail the reducer. The corresponding registry field is set to `null` so dashboard and registry refreshes still complete.\n470: \n471: For legal-stop replay, the reducer consumes `details.gateResults` from the latest `legal_stop_evaluated` event and surfaces it as `journalSummary.latestLegalStop.gateResults` in `experiment-registry.json` plus the dashboard's latest legal-stop table.\n472: \n473: ### Journal Replay Consumer\n474: \n475: The reducer consumes replay artifacts instead of running a separate orchestrator-only synthesis step. During each refresh pass, `scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs` reads the following artifacts when present:\n476: \n477: - `improvement-journal.jsonl` to summarize last session boundaries, total replayed events, per-event counts, and terminal `stopReason` / `sessionOutcome`\n478: - `candidate-lineage.json` to summarize lineage depth, total candidate count, and the latest candidate leaf\n479: - `mutation-coverage.json` to summarize mutation coverage ratio and uncovered mutations\n480: \n481: The reducer writes these summaries into new top-level registry fields:\n482: \n483: - `journalSummary`\n484: - `candidateLineage`\n485: - `mutationCoverage`\n486: \n487: Graceful degradation is required: if any artifact is missing, unreadable, or not yet generated for the current runtime, the reducer preserves the rest of the registry and records `null` for that field instead of throwing.\n488: \n489: The dashboard now also includes a dedicated **Sample Quality** section. This separates replay/stability sample sufficiency from benchmark failures so operators can tell the difference between a true regression and an iteration that simply lacked enough data for trade-off or replay-stability trust.\n490: \n491: ## 8. RULES\n492: \n493: ### ✅ ALWAYS\n494: \n495: - Read the charter, boundary file, and target profile before creating a candidate\n496: - Keep the ledger append-only\n497: - Treat the scorer as independent from the mutator\n498: - Preserve repeatability evidence when benchmark claims are made\n499: - Prefer the simpler candidate when scores tie\n500: - Keep benchmark evidence separate from mirror-drift packaging work\n501: - Require integration evidence to name each expected runtime mirror path explicitly (`.claude/agents`, `.codex/agents`, `.gemini/agents`, plus any declared extra mirrors) before trusting `integrationGate`\n502: \n503: ### ❌ NEVER\n504: \n505: - Mutate the canonical target during proposal-only mode\n506: - Broaden scope beyond the active boundary\n507: - Treat runtime mirrors as experiment truth in the same phase as canonical evaluation\n508: - Treat a stale placeholder mirror path as equivalent to a real runtime mirror\n509: - Hide rejected runs, weak benchmark results, or infra failures\n510: - Promote non-canonical targets even if they benchmark well\n511: \n512: ### ⚠️ ESCALATE IF\n513: \n514: - The target profile and boundary file disagree about mutability or target family\n515: - The benchmark runner cannot produce stable repeatability results\n516: - Promotion evidence is incomplete but canonical mutation is still being requested\n517: - Documentation edits would change the trust boundary rather than clarify it\n518: \n519: ---\n520: \n521: ## 9. REFERENCES\n522: \n523: Core references: `README.md`, `references/shared/quick_reference.md`, `references/shared/loop_protocol.md`, evaluator/promotion/rollback/no-go/onboarding docs, runtime assets under `assets/`, benchmark assets, and helper scripts for scoring, reduction, promotion, rollback, scanning, drift, journal, mutation coverage, trade-offs, candidate lineage, and benchmark stability.\n524: \n525: ---\n526: \n527: ## 10. INTEGRATION POINTS\n528: \n529: - `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` initializes and runs the Lane A bounded workflow\n530: - `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` initializes and runs the Lane B model-benchmark workflow\n531: - `.opencode/agents/deep-improvement.md` provides the mutator surface for deep-improvement runs\n532: - `sk-doc` validators enforce package-shape, README, and markdown document consistency\n533: - `system-spec-kit` packet validation proves phase records remain truthful\n534: \n535: ---\n536: \n537: ## 11. REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES\n538: \n539: The router discovers reference, asset, and script docs dynamically. Start with `references/shared/loop_protocol.md`, `references/shared/quick_reference.md`, `references/model-benchmark/benchmark_operator_guide.md`, `references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md`, `references/agent-improvement/integration_scanning.md`, `references/agent-improvement/mirror_drift_policy.md`, `references/shared/promotion_rules.md`, then load task-specific resources from `references/`, templates from `assets/`, and automation from `scripts/` when present.\n540: \n541: Scripts: `scripts/agent-improvement/benchmark-stability.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/candidate-lineage.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/check-mirror-drift.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/generate-profile.cjs`, `scripts/shared/improvement-journal.cjs`, `scripts/shared/materialize-benchmark-fixtures.cjs`, `scripts/shared/mutation-coverage.cjs`, `scripts/shared/promote-candidate.cjs`, `scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/rollback-candidate.cjs`, `scripts/model-benchmark/run-benchmark.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/scan-integration.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/score-candidate.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/trade-off-detector.cjs`.\n542: \n543: Related skills: `sk-doc` for package-shape and markdown validation, `system-spec-kit` for packet validation, and `sk-prompt` when prompt surfaces need evaluator-backed rewriting.\n\n(End of file - total 543 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: deep-improvement\ndescription: \"Evaluator-first bounded agent improvement: 5-dim scoring, dynamic profiling, packet-local candidates, guarded promotion.\"\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Glob, Grep]\nversion: 1.9.0.0\ntriggers:\n  - deep-improvement\n  - agent improvement loop\n  - bounded agent improvement\n  - 5-dimension scoring\n  - integration scanner\n  - dynamic profiling\n  - model-benchmark mode\n  - benchmark a model or prompt framework\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: deep-improvement, deep-improvement, agent-improvement, benchmark-harness, score-candidate, promote-candidate, rollback-candidate -->\n\n# Recursive Agent: Evaluator-First Improvement Orchestrator\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/deep-improvement/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1780204959707,"end":1780204959723}},"id":"prt_e7c7bf5a3001bQYH41TadOBAvQ","sessionID":"ses_183846c24ffe2Qtb7Q7eSJvXlI","messageID":"msg_e7c7bda26001QLqUg47WFBhmYt"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780204959726,"sessionID":"ses_183846c24ffe2Qtb7Q7eSJvXlI","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_ycc2i6htwgri_2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/README.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"deep-improvement: Prove an Agent Got Better Before You Ship It\"\n3: description: \"Evaluator-first skill for bounded agent improvement with 5-dimension integration-aware scoring, dynamic profiling, packet-local candidates, and guarded promotion or rollback.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"deep-improvement\"\n6:   - \"recursive agent\"\n7:   - \"agent improvement loop\"\n8:   - \"bounded agent improvement\"\n9:   - \"5-dimension scoring\"\n10:   - \"integration scanner\"\n11: ---\n12: \n13: # deep-improvement\n14: \n15: Improve an agent the way you ship code: change a copy, measure it, and promote only when the evidence holds.\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n20: \n21: ### What This Skill Does\n22: \n23: Editing an agent prompt is usually guesswork. You reword a rule, the prompt reads better, you ship it, and you never know whether the agent got stronger or only different. `deep-improvement` replaces that guess with measured evidence.\n24: \n25: The skill treats agent improvement as an optimization problem with a paper trail. It scans every surface an agent touches across the repo, derives a scoring profile from the agent's own rules, writes a candidate to a packet-local sandbox, scores it across five deterministic dimensions, and promotes to the canonical file only after evidence and an operator approval both pass. Nothing touches the real agent until you say so.\n26: \n27: For packet recovery around an improvement run, `/speckit:resume` stays the canonical surface. Continuity rebuilds from `handover.md`, then `_memory.continuity`, then the remaining spec docs.\n28: \n29: ### Three Lanes\n30: \n31: This skill runs three co-equal lanes that share one evaluator core, journal, and promotion discipline:\n32: \n33: | Lane | Use it to | Command |\n34: |---|---|---|\n35: | **Lane A — Agent-Improvement** | Improve a bounded agent `.md` file (the default; most of this README) | `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` |\n36: | **Lane B — Model-Benchmark** | Benchmark a model or prompt framework against fixtures | `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` |\n37: | **Lane C — Skill-Benchmark** | Diagnose a skill's real-world routing, discovery, efficiency, and usefulness | `/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop` |\n38: \n39: Lane B (the model-benchmark mode) is documented in `SKILL.md` §4 and `references/model-benchmark/`; Lane C (the skill-benchmark mode) in `references/skill-benchmark/`. To match the three lanes, `references/`, `assets/`, and `scripts/` are each split into `agent-improvement/`, `model-benchmark/`, `skill-benchmark/`, and `shared/` subdirs.\n40: \n41: ### What Changes With This Skill\n42: \n43: | Without it | With it |\n44: |---|---|\n45: | Prompt edits are ad hoc and untracked | Every candidate is packet-local and evidence-backed |\n46: | Quality is judged by reading the prompt file | Quality is scored across five deterministic dimensions |\n47: | Integration drift goes unnoticed | The scanner checks mirrors, commands, skills, and routing |\n48: | Promotion risk is hard to audit | Promotion, rollback, and drift review each leave explicit artifacts |\n49: | Only hand-profiled agents can be evaluated | Any agent in `.opencode/agents/` is evaluated through dynamic profiling |\n50: \n51: ### How This Compares\n52: \n53: The `@deep-improvement` agent (under `.opencode/agents/`) is the mutator that writes one candidate. This skill is the evaluator and the rulebook around it: it owns scoring, benchmarking, the promotion gates, and the stop logic. `sk-prompt` rewrites prompt prose on request. This skill decides whether a rewrite earned its place.\n54: \n55: ### Key Features at a Glance\n56: \n57: | Capability | What It Does |\n58: |---|---|\n59: | Integration scanning | Maps every file that references an agent across the repo |\n60: | Dynamic profiling | Derives scoring rules from the agent's own ALWAYS/NEVER/ESCALATE IF sections |\n61: | 5-dimension scoring | Measures structural integrity, rule coherence, integration consistency, output quality, and system fitness |\n62: | Proposal-first edits | Candidates live in a packet-local sandbox, never the canonical file |\n63: | Guarded promotion | Canonical mutation only after scoring, benchmark, repeatability, boundary, and approval all pass |\n64: | Rollback | Restores the pre-promotion backup and records a post-rollback dimensional snapshot |\n65: | Runtime-truth contracts | Stop-reason taxonomy, legal-stop gates, and an append-only journal, matching deep-research and deep-review |\n66: \n67: ### Requirements\n68: \n69: - An existing spec folder for the improvement run\n70: - Node.js 18+ for the `.cjs` scripts\n71: - A target agent file in `.opencode/agents/`\n72: - Packet-local runtime write access\n73: \n74: ---\n75: \n76: ## 2. QUICK START\n77: \n78: **Step 1: Pick a target and a spec folder.**\n79: \n80: Choose any agent under `.opencode/agents/` and the phase spec folder where the run will live.\n81: \n82: **Step 2: Run the loop.**\n83: \n84: ```text\n85: /deep:start-agent-improvement-loop \".opencode/agents/debug.md\" :confirm --spec-folder={spec_folder}\n86: ```\n87: \n88: Expected result: an integration scan, a packet-local candidate under `candidates/`, a five-dimension score, a benchmark report, and a refreshed dashboard.\n89: \n90: **Step 3: Run a single script when you only need one signal.**\n91: \n92: ```bash\n93: # Scan every surface the agent touches\n94: node .opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/agent-improvement/scan-integration.cjs --agent=debug\n95: \n96: # Derive a scoring profile from the agent itself\n97: node .opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/agent-improvement/generate-profile.cjs --agent=.opencode/agents/debug.md\n98: \n99: # Score across five dimensions (dynamic mode is the only path)\n100: node .opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/agent-improvement/score-candidate.cjs --candidate=.opencode/agents/debug.md\n101: ```\n102: \n103: Expected result: a JSON artifact with a five-dimension breakdown and a `candidate-acceptable` or `needs-improvement` recommendation.\n104: \n105: ---\n106: \n107: ## 3. FEATURES\n108: \n109: ### 3.1 EVALUATION LOOP\n110: \n111: The loop runs from fresh setup through proposal, scoring, and the stop decision. Six features carry it.\n112: \n113: - **Initialization.** Sets up a fresh packet-local session before any candidate work. It creates `{spec_folder}/improvement/`, scans the target surface, copies the config, charter, strategy, and manifest, and records baseline state so every later score has something to compare against.\n114: - **Candidate generation.** Writes exactly one bounded candidate under `candidates/` without touching the canonical target. Generation is delegated to the `@deep-improvement` agent, which reads the charter and manifest first and stops before scoring begins, which keeps the mutator and the evaluator independent.\n115: - **Scoring dispatch.** Routes a candidate through `score-candidate.cjs`, records mutation coverage, writes journal events, and refreshes the dashboard through `reduce-state.cjs`. This turns each iteration into append-only evidence instead of a one-off opinion.\n116: - **Promotion gates.** Define the narrow conditions under which a candidate becomes promotion-eligible: explicit approval, benchmark pass, repeatability pass, manifest compliance, and a meaningful score delta. The gate is stricter than the scorer on purpose so a marginal candidate cannot slip through.\n117: - **Rollback.** Restores the archived canonical target after a guarded promotion. Rollback is a separate helper, not a side effect of promotion, so recovery stays explicit and auditable.\n118: - **Plateau detection.** Stops the loop when repeated runs stop moving. `reduce-state.cjs` halts when every tracked dimension repeats its score across the plateau window, which prevents endless iterations that burn cost without improving anything.\n119: \n120: ### 3.2 INTEGRATION SCANNING\n121: \n122: An agent is more than its `.md` file. Three features map the full surface.\n123: \n124: - **Surface discovery.** `scan-integration.cjs` inventories the canonical agent file, three runtime mirrors, the `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` command markdown, YAML workflow assets, skill references, global docs, and the `system-skill-advisor` routing path. The score reflects the whole integration, not the prompt in isolation.\n125: - **Runtime mirrors.** Checks whether the runtime-specific mirrors still reflect the canonical body. Parity is signal-based: the scanner extracts emphasized strings from the canonical agent and marks a mirror aligned when enough of them appear, so a drifted mirror shows up before it causes a runtime surprise.\n126: - **Command dispatch.** Owns the path that turns the skill into a runnable loop. `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` collects setup inputs, picks `:auto` or `:confirm`, and points the operator at the matching YAML workflow, which is where the real agent dispatch and journal emission happen.\n127: \n128: ### 3.3 FIVE-DIMENSION SCORING\n129: \n130: Scoring is deterministic. Every check is regex, string match, or file existence, with no model-as-judge step. Four features build the scoring stack.\n131: \n132: - **Five-dimension rubric.** Judges a candidate across five weighted dimensions. Each has a concrete checker, so a score traces back to specific evidence rather than a vibe.\n133: \n134: | Dimension | Weight | What It Measures |\n135: |---|---|---|\n136: | Structural integrity | 0.20 | Required agent sections are present |\n137: | Rule coherence | 0.25 | ALWAYS/NEVER rules align with the workflow steps |\n138: | Integration consistency | 0.25 | Mirrors in sync, commands and skills reference the agent |\n139: | Output quality | 0.15 | Output-verification items present, no placeholder content |\n140: | System fitness | 0.15 | Permissions match capabilities, resource references resolve, frontmatter complete |\n141: \n142: - **Dynamic profiling.** Generates a target-specific profile straight from the agent being scored. No static profiles ship, so any agent in `.opencode/agents/` is a valid target the moment it exists, with the selection rationale recorded for audit.\n143: - **Deterministic scoring.** `score-candidate.cjs` always runs in `dynamic-5d` mode, regenerates the profile every run, and emits structured dimension details plus a `candidate-acceptable` or `needs-improvement` verdict. A weighted score of 70 or higher reads as acceptable.\n144: - **Dimensional progress.** `reduce-state.cjs` aggregates the JSONL ledger into `experiment-registry.json` and a dashboard, records the latest and best value per dimension, and computes stop status, so an operator can see the trend instead of squinting at raw runs.\n145: \n146: ### 3.4 RUNTIME-TRUTH CONTRACTS\n147: \n148: These contracts match the deep-research and deep-review runtime-truth model so the three loops report termination the same way.\n149: \n150: - **Stop-reason taxonomy.** Every session ends with both a `stopReason` (why) and a `sessionOutcome` (what happened to the candidate), drawn from frozen enums, so a stopped run is never ambiguous.\n151: - **Audit journal.** `improvement-journal.cjs` writes an append-only `improvement-journal.jsonl` of lifecycle events. Emission is orchestrator-only, so the agent under evaluation never forges its own evidence.\n152: - **Legal-stop gates.** A session may claim `converged` only when all five gate bundles pass: contract, behavior, integration, evidence, and improvement. A failure emits `blocked_stop` with the failing gates named.\n153: - **Mutation coverage graph.** `mutation-coverage.cjs` tracks explored dimensions and tried mutation types under a `loop_type: \"improvement\"` namespace, with a signature dedup that skips a mutation already attempted, so the loop stops re-trying what it already ruled out.\n154: - **Trade-off detection.** `trade-off-detector.cjs` flags Pareto trade-offs where a gain in one dimension forces a regression in a hard dimension, and blocks promotion for a dominated candidate.\n155: \n156: ### 3.5 MULTI-ITER METHODOLOGY\n157: \n158: For multi-iter evaluation sweeps, two patterns improve breadth and cut noise.\n159: \n160: - **Mixed-executor dispatch.** Runs breadth iterations on cli-devin SWE-1.6 and synthesis iterations on cli-codex gpt-5.5 in an 8+2 split, which balances exploration cost against synthesis quality.\n161: - **Adjudication-iter filter.** Adds a false-positive filter pass before synthesis, typically at the iteration-7 mark, so only confirmed findings reach the synthesis iterations. See `references/model-benchmark/mixed_executor_methodology.md` for the split mechanics and adjudication details.\n162: \n163: ---\n164: \n165: ## 4. STRUCTURE\n166: \n167: ```text\n168: .opencode/skills/deep-improvement/\n169: +-- SKILL.md                    # Router and runtime instructions (three co-equal lanes)\n170: +-- README.md                   # This file\n171: +-- references/                 # operator and policy guides, grouped by lane\n172: |   +-- agent-improvement/      # Lane A (6): integration, scoring, profiling, onboarding, proposal, mirror drift\n173: |   +-- model-benchmark/        # Lane B (3): evaluator contract, benchmark operator guide, mixed-executor\n174: |   `-- shared/                 # both lanes (5): quick reference, loop protocol, promotion rules + gate, rollback\n175: +-- assets/                     # grouped by lane\n176: |   +-- agent-improvement/      # Lane A: charter, strategy, config, manifest\n177: |   `-- model-benchmark/        # Lane B: benchmark fixtures + profiles\n178: +-- scripts/                    # grouped by lane (16 helpers) + lib/ + tests/\n179: |   +-- agent-improvement/      # Lane A (8): scan, profile, score, rollback, drift, trade-off, lineage, stability\n180: |   +-- model-benchmark/        # Lane B (2): run-benchmark, dispatch-model + scorer/ subtree\n181: |   `-- shared/                 # both lanes (6): loop-host, reduce-state, promote, journal, coverage, materialize\n182: +-- feature_catalog/            # Current-state feature inventory (4 categories incl. model-benchmark)\n183: `-- manual_testing_playbook/    # 42 manual scenarios across 9 categories (09 = model-benchmark / Lane B)\n184: ```\n185: \n186: ### References (14, grouped by lane)\n187: \n188: Under `references/agent-improvement/` (6), `references/model-benchmark/` (3), and `references/shared/` (5).\n189: \n190: | Reference | Purpose |\n191: |---|---|\n192: | `quick_reference.md` | Command and dimension reminder (always loaded) |\n193: | `loop_protocol.md` | End-to-end operator workflow |\n194: | `evaluator_contract.md` | Scoring and benchmark contract |\n195: | `score_dimensions.md` | Per-dimension checker detail |\n196: | `benchmark_operator_guide.md` | Fixture benchmark execution |\n197: | `candidate_proposal_format.md` | Shape of a packet-local candidate |\n198: | `promotion_rules.md` | Keep, reject, promote decisions |\n199: | `promotion_gate_contract.md` | Gate contract the promotion helper enforces |\n200: | `rollback_runbook.md` | Promotion rollback procedure |\n201: | `mirror_drift_policy.md` | Mirror packaging policy |\n202: | `target_onboarding.md` | Adding new bounded targets |\n203: | `integration_scanning.md` | Integration scanner documentation |\n204: | `profiling_audit_log.md` | Profile-selection rationale logging |\n205: | `mixed_executor_methodology.md` | Mixed-executor and adjudication-iter guidance |\n206: \n207: ### Scripts (16 + lib, grouped by lane)\n208: \n209: Under `scripts/agent-improvement/` (8), `scripts/model-benchmark/` (2, plus the `scorer/` subtree), and `scripts/shared/` (6), with `lib/` helpers and `tests/`.\n210: \n211: | Script | Purpose |\n212: |---|---|\n213: | `shared/loop-host.cjs` | Mode-switch entry point: routes to Lane A or `--mode=model-benchmark` (Lane B) |\n214: | `model-benchmark/dispatch-model.cjs` | Lane B: run a model against fixtures under prompt-framework variants |\n215: | `model-benchmark/scorer/**` | Lane B: ported decoupled scorer (deterministic checks + LLM grader harness) |\n216: | `scan-integration.cjs` | Discover every surface an agent touches |\n217: | `generate-profile.cjs` | Derive a scoring profile from any agent |\n218: | `score-candidate.cjs` | Score a candidate across five dimensions |\n219: | `run-benchmark.cjs` | Run fixture tests plus integration checks |\n220: | `reduce-state.cjs` | Refresh dashboard and registry from the ledger |\n221: | `promote-candidate.cjs` | Guarded canonical promotion |\n222: | `rollback-candidate.cjs` | Restore the pre-promotion backup |\n223: | `check-mirror-drift.cjs` | Report declared-surface alignment |\n224: | `improvement-journal.cjs` | Append-only lifecycle journal emitter |\n225: | `mutation-coverage.cjs` | Track explored dimensions and mutation types |\n226: | `trade-off-detector.cjs` | Flag and block Pareto-dominated candidates |\n227: | `candidate-lineage.cjs` | Track candidate parentage across waves |\n228: | `benchmark-stability.cjs` | Repeatability and weight-recommendation report |\n229: | `materialize-benchmark-fixtures.cjs` | Render static fixtures into packet-local outputs |\n230: | `lib/promotion-gates.cjs`, `lib/mirror-sync-verify.cjs`, `lib/typed-errors.cjs` | Shared helpers for gates, mirror checks, and typed errors |\n231: \n232: ### Assets and Catalog\n233: \n234: | Path | Purpose |\n235: |---|---|\n236: | `assets/agent-improvement/improvement_config.json` | Runtime config: weights, stop rules, feature flags |\n237: | `assets/agent-improvement/improvement_config_reference.md` | Field-level config documentation |\n238: | `assets/agent-improvement/improvement_charter.md` | Fixed policy charter template |\n239: | `assets/agent-improvement/improvement_strategy.md` | Mutable runtime strategy template |\n240: | `assets/agent-improvement/target_manifest.jsonc` | Target classification and mutability |\n241: | `assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-fixtures/*.json` | Baseline, edge, and improved benchmark fixtures |\n242: | `assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/default.json` | Default benchmark profile |\n243: | `feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md` | Current-state feature inventory with source anchors |\n244: \n245: ---\n246: \n247: ## 5. CONFIGURATION\n248: \n249: | Setting | Default | Effect |\n250: |---|---|---|\n251: | `proposalOnly` | `true` | Candidates cannot be promoted until flipped |\n252: | `dynamicProfileEnabled` | `true` | Required. Dynamic mode is the sole scoring path |\n253: | `dimensionWeights` | `{structural: 0.20, ruleCoherence: 0.25, ...}` | Weights for the five-dimension score |\n254: | `stopOnDimensionPlateau` | `true` | Stop when all dimensions plateau |\n255: | `thresholdDelta` | `2` | Minimum score improvement for `candidate-better` |\n256: | `minimumAggregateScore` | `85` | Benchmark pass threshold |\n257: \n258: Field-level documentation lives in `assets/agent-improvement/improvement_config_reference.md`. Target classification and mutability live in `assets/agent-improvement/target_manifest.jsonc`.\n259: \n260: ### Runtime Parity\n261: \n262: The `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` command and the `@deep-improvement` agent are mirrored across runtimes. The integration scanner checks mirror parity on every run.\n263: \n264: | Runtime | Agent Path | Command Path |\n265: |---|---|---|\n266: | OpenCode / Copilot | `.opencode/agents/` | `.opencode/commands/deep/` |\n267: | Claude | `.claude/agents/` | uses agent mirror |\n268: | Codex | `.codex/agents/` | uses agent mirror |\n269: | Gemini | `.gemini/agents/` | uses agent mirror |\n270: \n271: ---\n272: \n273: ## 6. USAGE EXAMPLES\n274: \n275: **Evaluate any agent (dynamic mode)**\n276: \n277: ```text\n278: User request: improve the debug agent\n279: Skill routing: /deep:start-agent-improvement-loop \".opencode/agents/debug.md\" :confirm --spec-folder={spec_folder}\n280: Resources loaded: charter, manifest, target profile (generated on the fly)\n281: Expected output: five-dimension score plus a packet-local candidate, no canonical change\n282: ```\n283: \n284: **Quick integration health check**\n285: \n286: ```bash\n287: node .opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/agent-improvement/scan-integration.cjs --agent=review\n288: ```\n289: \n290: Expected output: mirror sync status, command coverage, and skill references for the review agent.\n291: \n292: **Inspect runtime evidence after a run**\n293: \n294: ```text\n295: {spec_folder}/improvement/agent-improvement-dashboard.md   # dimensional progress and stop status\n296: {spec_folder}/improvement/experiment-registry.json          # per-profile metrics and best-known state\n297: {spec_folder}/improvement/integration-report.json           # integration surface inventory\n298: ```\n299: \n300: ---\n301: \n302: ## 7. TROUBLESHOOTING\n303: \n304: | What You See | Likely Cause | Fix |\n305: |---|---|---|\n306: | Candidate scores well but benchmark fails | Output contract is weaker than the prompt | Read the target fixtures and rerun |\n307: | Benchmark scores drift across repeats | Fixtures are unstable | Treat the run as untrustworthy until repeatability is fixed |\n308: | Promotion is refused | A promotion gate is missing | Check score delta, benchmark report, repeatability, target, and approval |\n309: | Mirrors differ after promotion | Packaging drift not handled yet | Run `scan-integration.cjs` and record follow-up sync work |\n310: | Scorer returns 0 on all dimensions | Profile generation failed | Run `generate-profile.cjs` directly and check for parse errors |\n311: | All dimensions plateaued | The current hypothesis is exhausted | Reassess the hypothesis in `improvement_strategy.md` |\n312: | Scorer reports `infra_failure` | Agent file not found or unreadable | Verify the `--candidate` path is a valid agent `.md` |\n313: \n314: ---\n315: \n316: ## 8. FAQ\n317: \n318: **Q: Why not edit the canonical agent directly?**\n319: \n320: A: The point is to prove improvement before mutation. Direct edits skip the evidence trail that makes a promotion decision auditable and a rollback possible.\n321: \n322: **Q: How is promotion eligibility decided?**\n323: \n324: A: A candidate becomes eligible only when prompt scoring, benchmark status, repeatability evidence, manifest boundary compliance, and explicit operator approval all pass for that specific target.\n325: \n326: **Q: What does the integration scanner check?**\n327: \n328: A: It finds every file that references an agent: the canonical definition, three runtime mirrors, command dispatch files, YAML workflow references, skill SKILL.md mentions, global docs, and the skill-advisor routing entry.\n329: \n330: **Q: How are agents evaluated?**\n331: \n332: A: Dynamic mode is the only path. The profile generator derives scoring checks from the agent's own ALWAYS/NEVER rules, output-verification checklist, capability scan, and anti-patterns. Any agent in `.opencode/agents/` is a valid target.\n333: \n334: **Q: What happens when all dimensions plateau?**\n335: \n336: A: When all five dimensions repeat their scores across the plateau window, the reducer triggers `stopOnDimensionPlateau`. The current improvement hypothesis is exhausted, so update the strategy before continuing.\n337: \n338: ---\n339: \n340: ## 9. RELATED DOCUMENTS\n341: \n342: ### Core References\n343: \n344: | Document | Purpose |\n345: |---|---|\n346: | [`SKILL.md`](./SKILL.md) | Router and runtime instructions |\n347: | [`feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md`](./feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md) | Current-state feature inventory across the three categories |\n348: | [`references/shared/quick_reference.md`](./references/shared/quick_reference.md) | Command and dimension reminder |\n349: | [`references/shared/loop_protocol.md`](./references/shared/loop_protocol.md) | End-to-end operator workflow |\n350: | [`references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md`](./references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md) | Five-dimension scoring and benchmark contract |\n351: \n352: ### Cross-System Connections\n353: \n354: | Target | Relationship |\n355: |---|---|\n356: | `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` (`.opencode/commands/deep/start-agent-improvement-loop.md`) | Initializes and runs the bounded workflow |\n357: | `@deep-improvement` (`.opencode/agents/deep-improvement.md`) | The mutator surface that writes one candidate |\n358: | [`sk-doc`](../sk-doc/SKILL.md) | Validates package shape, README, and markdown consistency |\n359: | [`system-spec-kit`](../system-spec-kit/SKILL.md) | Packet validation and continuity for the improvement run |\n360: | [`sk-prompt`](../sk-prompt/SKILL.md) | Rewrites prompt surfaces when a candidate needs new prose |\n361: | [`deep-research`](../deep-research/SKILL.md), [`deep-review`](../deep-review/SKILL.md) | Share the runtime-truth contract (stop reasons, legal-stop gates, journal) |\n362: | `cli-devin`, `cli-codex` | Executors for the mixed-executor multi-iter methodology |\n363: | `system-skill-advisor` | Routes requests to this skill and is checked by the integration scanner |\n\n(End of file - total 363 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"deep-improvement: Prove an Agent Got Better Before You Ship It\"\ndescription: \"Evaluator-first skill for bounded agent improvement with 5-dimension integration-aware scoring, dynamic profiling, packet-local candidates, and guarded promotion or rollback.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"deep-improvement\"\n  - \"recursive agent\"\n  - \"agent improvement loop\"\n  - \"bounded agent improvement\"\n  - \"5-dimension scoring\"\n  - \"integration scanner\"\n---\n\n# deep-improvement\n\nImprove an agent the way you ship code: change a copy, measure it, and promote only when the evidence holds.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/deep-improvement/README.md","time":{"start":1780204959715,"end":1780204959725}},"id":"prt_e7c7bf7df001BOiJiFsMWr8bUz","sessionID":"ses_183846c24ffe2Qtb7Q7eSJvXlI","messageID":"msg_e7c7bda26001QLqUg47WFBhmYt"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780204960095,"sessionID":"ses_183846c24ffe2Qtb7Q7eSJvXlI","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_ycc2i6htwgri_3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"deep-improvement: Feature Catalog\"\n3: description: \"Unified reference combining the evaluation loop, integration scanning, scoring, model-benchmark mode, and skill-benchmark mode surfaces that currently ship in deep-improvement.\"\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # deep-improvement: Feature Catalog\n7: \n8: This document combines the current feature inventory for the `deep-improvement` system into a single reference. The root catalog acts as the system-level directory: it summarizes the evaluation loop, the integration scanner, the deterministic scoring stack, the model-benchmark mode, and the skill-benchmark mode, then points to the per-feature files that carry the deeper implementation and validation anchors.\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n13: \n14: Use this catalog as the canonical inventory for the live `deep-improvement` feature surface. The numbered sections below group the skill by runtime responsibility so readers can move from a top-level summary into per-feature reference files without losing the current code and operator-contract context behind each claim.\n15: \n16: ### Lane Legend\n17: \n18: The skill runs three lanes through one agent. Each category and feature below is tagged with the lane it serves.\n19: \n20: | Lane | Meaning | Entry Point |\n21: |---|---|---|\n22: | **Lane A** | Agent-improvement: evaluate and improve an agent markdown file via guarded promotion | `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`, `loop-host --mode=agent-improvement` |\n23: | **Lane B** | Model-benchmark: benchmark a model or prompt framework, no agent mutation | `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop`, `loop-host --mode=model-benchmark` |\n24: | **Lane C** | Skill-benchmark: diagnose a skill's routing, discovery, efficiency, and usefulness, no skill mutation | `/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop`, `loop-host --mode=skill-benchmark` |\n25: | **Shared** | Surface used by all lanes (reducer, dashboard, profiling, command scaffolding) | reached from any lane |\n26: \n27: | Category | Coverage | Lane | Primary Runtime Surface |\n28: |---|---:|---|---|\n29: | Evaluation loop | 6 features | Lane A | `.opencode/commands/deep/start-agent-improvement-loop.md`, deep-improvement YAML workflows, `scripts/*.cjs` |\n30: | Integration scanning | 3 features | Lane A | `scan-integration.cjs`, `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`, `.opencode/agents/deep-improvement.md` |\n31: | Scoring system | 4 features | Shared | `generate-profile.cjs`, `score-candidate.cjs`, `reduce-state.cjs` |\n32: | Model-benchmark mode | 4 features | Lane B | `loop-host.cjs`, `dispatch-model.cjs`, `run-benchmark.cjs`, `scorer/score-model-variant.cjs` |\n33: | Skill-benchmark mode | 6 features | Lane C | `loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark`, `scripts/skill-benchmark/*.cjs` |\n34: \n35: ---\n36: \n37: ## 2. EVALUATION LOOP\n38: \n39: **Lane:** Lane A (agent-improvement)\n40: \n41: These entries cover the session lifecycle from fresh runtime setup through proposal-only candidate generation, scoring dispatch, guarded promotion, rollback, and the stop logic that decides when the loop should stop asking for more iterations.\n42: \n43: ### Initialization\n44: \n45: #### Description\n46: \n47: Sets up a fresh packet-local deep-improvement session before any candidate work begins.\n48: \n49: #### Current Reality\n50: \n51: The shipped workflow only supports fresh `new` sessions. Both YAML workflows create `{spec_folder}/improvement/`, scan the target integration surface, generate a dynamic profile when requested, copy the config, strategy, charter, and manifest templates, record baseline state, and emit a `session_start` journal row before iteration one.\n52: \n53: #### Source Files\n54: \n55: See [`01--evaluation-loop/01-initialization.md`](01--evaluation-loop/01-initialization.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n56: \n57: ---\n58: \n59: ### Candidate generation\n60: \n61: #### Description\n62: \n63: Writes one bounded packet-local candidate without mutating the canonical target.\n64: \n65: #### Current Reality\n66: \n67: Candidate generation is delegated to the `deep-improvement` subagent. That agent must read the copied charter and manifest first, must write only under the packet-local runtime area, returns structured metadata, and stops before scoring, benchmarking, promotion, or mirror synchronization begins.\n68: \n69: #### Source Files\n70: \n71: See [`01--evaluation-loop/02-candidate-generation.md`](01--evaluation-loop/02-candidate-generation.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n72: \n73: ---\n74: \n75: ### Scoring dispatch\n76: \n77: #### Description\n78: \n79: Routes a generated candidate through scoring, evidence recording, and state reduction.\n80: \n81: #### Current Reality\n82: \n83: The loop dispatches `score-candidate.cjs`, records mutation coverage, writes journal events, and refreshes the dashboard with `reduce-state.cjs`. Benchmark stability and trade-off checks are wired as concrete commands, while the benchmark runner itself still appears as an action placeholder in the YAML workflows, so fully automatic benchmark execution depends on operator wiring or wrapper logic outside the YAML text.\n84: \n85: #### Source Files\n86: \n87: See [`01--evaluation-loop/03-scoring-dispatch.md`](01--evaluation-loop/03-scoring-dispatch.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n88: \n89: ---\n90: \n91: ### Promotion gates\n92: \n93: #### Description\n94: \n95: Defines the narrow conditions under which a packet-local candidate can become promotion-eligible.\n96: \n97: #### Current Reality\n98: \n99: The policy surface requires explicit approval, benchmark pass, repeatability pass, manifest compliance, and a meaningful improvement threshold. The promotion helper is stricter than the current scorer output: it still requires `candidate-better` plus `score.delta`, while `score-candidate.cjs` currently emits `candidate-acceptable` or `needs-improvement` and does not add a delta field.\n100: \n101: #### Source Files\n102: \n103: See [`01--evaluation-loop/04-promotion-gates.md`](01--evaluation-loop/04-promotion-gates.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n104: \n105: ---\n106: \n107: ### Rollback\n108: \n109: #### Description\n110: \n111: Restores the archived canonical target after a guarded promotion has already happened.\n112: \n113: #### Current Reality\n114: \n115: Rollback is a separate helper, not an implicit part of promotion. The shipped rollback script validates the runtime config target and the single canonical target in the manifest, then copies the saved backup over the canonical file; journal emission, mirror review, and post-rollback re-scoring remain separate orchestration steps.\n116: \n117: #### Source Files\n118: \n119: See [`01--evaluation-loop/05-rollback.md`](01--evaluation-loop/05-rollback.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n120: \n121: ---\n122: \n123: ### Plateau detection\n124: \n125: #### Description\n126: \n127: Stops the loop when repeated runs no longer produce useful movement.\n128: \n129: #### Current Reality\n130: \n131: Two stop models are live. `reduce-state.cjs` can stop when all tracked dimensions plateau with exact repeated scores across the configured plateau window, while `mutation-coverage.cjs`, `trade-off-detector.cjs`, and `benchmark-stability.cjs` separately gate convergence, trade-off analysis, and replay stability behind a minimum of three scored samples.\n132: \n133: #### Source Files\n134: \n135: See [`01--evaluation-loop/06-plateau-detection.md`](01--evaluation-loop/06-plateau-detection.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n136: \n137: ---\n138: \n139: ## 3. INTEGRATION SCANNING\n140: \n141: **Lane:** Lane A (agent-improvement)\n142: \n143: These entries describe how deep-improvement discovers the full agent surface across the repo, evaluates runtime mirrors, and wires command-driven orchestration through the deep-improvement command and YAML workflows.\n144: \n145: ### Surface discovery\n146: \n147: #### Description\n148: \n149: Builds the inventory of files and references that define an agent beyond its canonical markdown file.\n150: \n151: #### Current Reality\n152: \n153: `scan-integration.cjs` scans the canonical agent file, three runtime mirrors, improve command markdown, YAML workflow assets, skill references, global docs, and a skill-advisor path constant. That path now points at `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill_advisor.py`, so the consolidated skill-advisor surface is included in the integration map.\n154: \n155: #### Source Files\n156: \n157: See [`02--integration-scanning/01-surface-discovery.md`](02--integration-scanning/01-surface-discovery.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n158: \n159: ---\n160: \n161: ### Runtime mirrors\n162: \n163: #### Description\n164: \n165: Checks whether the runtime-specific mirrors still reflect the canonical agent body closely enough.\n166: \n167: #### Current Reality\n168: \n169: Mirror parity is signal-based, not byte-for-byte. The scanner strips frontmatter, extracts up to three emphasized signal strings from the canonical body, and marks a mirror `aligned` when at least two signals appear in the mirror body. It checks `.claude/agents`, `.codex/agents`, and `.gemini/agents` against the canonical `.opencode/agents`.\n170: \n171: #### Source Files\n172: \n173: See [`02--integration-scanning/02-runtime-mirrors.md`](02--integration-scanning/02-runtime-mirrors.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n174: \n175: ---\n176: \n177: ### Command dispatch\n178: \n179: #### Description\n180: \n181: Owns the command-driven orchestration path that turns the deep-improvement skill into a runnable loop.\n182: \n183: #### Current Reality\n184: \n185: The `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` command collects setup inputs, selects `:auto` or `:confirm` execution, and points the operator at the matching YAML workflow. The actual loop dispatch lives in the YAML assets, which rescan integration, dispatch `@deep-improvement`, emit journal events, and call score and reducer helpers, while the command markdown explicitly says not to dispatch agents from the command file itself.\n186: \n187: #### Source Files\n188: \n189: See [`02--integration-scanning/03-command-dispatch.md`](02--integration-scanning/03-command-dispatch.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n190: \n191: ---\n192: \n193: ## 4. SCORING SYSTEM\n194: \n195: **Lane:** Shared (Lane A scores candidates, Lane B can opt into the same 5-dim scorer)\n196: \n197: These entries describe the dynamic scoring stack that derives evaluation structure from the target agent, applies the five-dimension rubric, records deterministic score outputs, and turns repeated runs into dimensional progress and stop-state summaries.\n198: \n199: ### Five-dimension rubric\n200: \n201: #### Description\n202: \n203: Defines the weighted evaluation model used to judge prompt-surface quality.\n204: \n205: #### Current Reality\n206: \n207: Dynamic scoring uses five weighted dimensions: structural integrity, rule coherence, integration consistency, output quality, and system fitness. Each dimension has a concrete checker in `score-candidate.cjs`, with integration itself delegated to the integration scanner and output quality penalized when placeholder strings remain in the candidate.\n208: \n209: #### Source Files\n210: \n211: See [`03--scoring-system/01-five-dimension-rubric.md`](03--scoring-system/01-five-dimension-rubric.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n212: \n213: ---\n214: \n215: ### Dynamic profiling\n216: \n217: #### Description\n218: \n219: Generates a target-specific evaluation profile directly from the agent being scored.\n220: \n221: #### Current Reality\n222: \n223: No static evaluation profiles ship in the current release. `generate-profile.cjs` parses frontmatter, sections, rules, output checklists, related-resource tables, and denied permissions to build a derived profile on the fly, while `target_manifest.jsonc` keeps `targets` empty and points runtime consumers at the dynamic-profile script instead of a fixed catalog.\n224: \n225: #### Source Files\n226: \n227: See [`03--scoring-system/02-dynamic-profiling.md`](03--scoring-system/02-dynamic-profiling.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n228: \n229: ---\n230: \n231: ### Deterministic scoring\n232: \n233: #### Description\n234: \n235: Produces the score and benchmark evidence that later gates consume.\n236: \n237: #### Current Reality\n238: \n239: `score-candidate.cjs` always runs in `dynamic-5d` mode, regenerates the profile every run, allows optional weight overrides, and emits structured dimension details plus `candidate-acceptable` or `needs-improvement`. `run-benchmark.cjs` is also deterministic, but it still expects a profile JSON and fixture directory under `assets/agent-improvement/target-profiles`, so benchmark gating only becomes runnable when that profile-specific artifact set exists.\n240: \n241: #### Source Files\n242: \n243: See [`03--scoring-system/03-deterministic-scoring.md`](03--scoring-system/03-deterministic-scoring.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n244: \n245: ---\n246: \n247: ### Dimensional progress\n248: \n249: #### Description\n250: \n251: Reduces raw run records into trends, best-known state, and operator-facing stop guidance.\n252: \n253: #### Current Reality\n254: \n255: `reduce-state.cjs` aggregates the JSONL ledger into `experiment-registry.json` and `agent-improvement-dashboard.md`, records latest and best values per dimension, adds sample-quality, journal, lineage, and mutation-coverage summaries, and computes stop status. It treats both `candidate-acceptable` and `candidate-better` as accepted candidates when building the registry.\n256: \n257: #### Source Files\n258: \n259: See [`03--scoring-system/04-dimensional-progress.md`](03--scoring-system/04-dimensional-progress.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n260: \n261: ---\n262: \n263: ## 5. MODEL-BENCHMARK MODE\n264: \n265: **Lane:** Lane B (model-benchmark)\n266: \n267: These entries describe the model-benchmark path that benchmarks a model or prompt framework instead of mutating an agent file. They cover the mode switch in the loop host, the model-agnostic dispatcher, the opt-in five-dimension scorer, and the record-level mode field plus the two hardening env gates.\n268: \n269: ### Mode switch\n270: \n271: #### Description\n272: \n273: Routes loop-host between the agent-improvement scorer and the model-benchmark materialize-then-run pipeline.\n274: \n275: #### Current Reality\n276: \n277: `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs` resolves `--mode` before any work begins. `--mode=agent-improvement`, or no flag, routes to `scripts/agent-improvement/score-candidate.cjs` unchanged, while `--mode=model-benchmark` runs `scripts/shared/materialize-benchmark-fixtures.cjs` then `scripts/model-benchmark/run-benchmark.cjs`. `VALID_MODES` is a closed two-value set, and an unknown mode warns to stderr and falls back to `agent-improvement`.\n278: \n279: #### Source Files\n280: \n281: See [`04--model-benchmark-mode/01-mode-switch.md`](04--model-benchmark-mode/01-mode-switch.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n282: \n283: ---\n284: \n285: ### Model dispatcher\n286: \n287: #### Description\n288: \n289: Model-agnostic dispatcher that routes prompts across executor CLIs only on the model-benchmark path.\n290: \n291: #### Current Reality\n292: \n293: `scripts/model-benchmark/dispatch-model.cjs` routes through an executor map across cli-opencode, cli-claude-code, cli-codex, cli-gemini, and cli-devin, and is loaded only on the model-benchmark path, never in agent-improvement mode. It forwards `cwd` to every executor and applies rate-limit backoff using a non-busy `Atomics` sleep.\n294: \n295: #### Source Files\n296: \n297: See [`04--model-benchmark-mode/02-model-dispatcher.md`](04--model-benchmark-mode/02-model-dispatcher.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n298: \n299: ---\n300: \n301: ### Opt-in 5-dimension scorer\n302: \n303: #### Description\n304: \n305: Selects the pattern matcher by default or the opt-in five-dimension scorer for model-benchmark outputs.\n306: \n307: #### Current Reality\n308: \n309: `run-benchmark.cjs --scorer pattern` is the default byte-identical heading and pattern matcher, while `--scorer 5dim` routes materialized outputs through `scripts/model-benchmark/scorer/score-model-variant.cjs`, the ported five-dimension scorer. `--grader noop` is the default deterministic grader with no model dispatch, with `--grader mock` and `--grader llm` selecting the stub or real grader, and the report carries `scoringMethod: pattern` or `scoringMethod: 5dim`.\n310: \n311: #### Source Files\n312: \n313: See [`04--model-benchmark-mode/03-opt-in-5dim-scorer.md`](04--model-benchmark-mode/03-opt-in-5dim-scorer.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n314: \n315: ---\n316: \n317: ### Mode records and hardening gates\n318: \n319: #### Description\n320: \n321: Stamps a mode field on every state record and exposes two env gates that harden the 5-dim scorer.\n322: \n323: #### Current Reality\n324: \n325: Every state record carries `mode: agent-improvement` or `mode: model-benchmark`, and benchmark reports plus `benchmark_run` records carry `scoringMethod: pattern|5dim`. `DEEP_AGENT_ALLOW_CRITERIA_EXEC=0` refuses criteria-driven shell execution in the 5-dim scorer, and `DEEP_AGENT_GRADER_CACHE_RAW=0` redacts raw grader output from the on-disk cache. Both default to the permissive value for backward-compat.\n326: \n327: #### Source Files\n328: \n329: See [`04--model-benchmark-mode/04-mode-records-and-gates.md`](04--model-benchmark-mode/04-mode-records-and-gates.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n330: \n331: ---\n332: \n333: ## 6. SKILL-BENCHMARK MODE\n334: \n335: **Lane:** Lane C (skill-benchmark)\n336: \n337: These entries describe the skill-benchmark path that diagnoses how a *skill* is routed-to, discovered, used, and structured in practice — distinct from doc-shape validation and manual testing playbooks. It is diagnostic by default and emits a ranked Skill Benchmark Report. Mode A (router-replay) and D1-inter (advisor probe) are deterministic; D4 usefulness ablation and live trace capture are follow-on.\n338: \n339: ### Mode wiring and orchestration\n340: \n341: #### Description\n342: \n343: Routes loop-host to the skill-benchmark orchestrator with a single additive arm; the orchestrator runs the D5 gate, then per-scenario contamination-lint, router-replay, and scoring.\n344: \n345: #### Current Reality\n346: \n347: `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs` resolves `--mode=skill-benchmark` to `scripts/skill-benchmark/run-skill-benchmark.cjs` via an additive `VALID_MODES` entry, `LANE_SKILL_BENCHMARK` set, and `planInvocation` arm; the agent-improvement and model-benchmark plans stay byte-identical.\n348: \n349: #### Source Files\n350: \n351: `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs`, `scripts/skill-benchmark/run-skill-benchmark.cjs`.\n352: \n353: ### Hint-free fixtures and contamination gate\n354: \n355: #### Description\n356: \n357: Per-skill public/private scenario fixtures keep the expected skill/intents/resources scorer-only; a contamination linter rejects public prompts that leak the answer before dispatch.\n358: \n359: #### Current Reality\n360: \n361: `scripts/skill-benchmark/contamination-lint.cjs` builds banned vocabulary from the target skill's own identity (name, triggers, router keywords, resource path tokens) and treats any leak as a fixture failure, not a skill failure.\n362: \n363: #### Source Files\n364: \n365: `scripts/skill-benchmark/contamination-lint.cjs`, `assets/skill-benchmark/fixtures/`.\n366: \n367: ### Router-replay and advisor probe (Mode A)\n368: \n369: #### Description\n370: \n371: Replays the target skill's own router for in-skill routing and discovery, and probes the advisor out-of-band for inter-skill selection — both deterministic, no LLM.\n372: \n373: #### Current Reality\n374: \n375: `scripts/skill-benchmark/router-replay.cjs` extracts `INTENT_SIGNALS`/`RESOURCE_MAP` from the target `SKILL.md` and reproduces the substring routing (D1-intra + D2 proxy); `scripts/skill-benchmark/advisor-probe.cjs` runs `skill_advisor.py` over the SQLite graph for the D1-inter signal.\n376: \n377: #### Source Files\n378: \n379: `scripts/skill-benchmark/router-replay.cjs`, `scripts/skill-benchmark/advisor-probe.cjs`.\n380: \n381: ### D5 structural connectivity hard gate\n382: \n383: #### Description\n384: \n385: A static scan runs before any dispatch and caps the verdict on structural failures.\n386: \n387: #### Current Reality\n388: \n389: `scripts/skill-benchmark/d5-connectivity.cjs` flags dead routed paths, dead intent keys, path escapes, orphan references, and an unparseable router; any P0 sets `gateFailed` and caps the verdict to `BLOCKED-BY-STRUCTURE`.\n390: \n391: #### Source Files\n392: \n393: `scripts/skill-benchmark/d5-connectivity.cjs`.\n394: \n395: ### D1-D5 scoring and funnel\n396: \n397: #### Description\n398: \n399: Computes the five dimensions with a funnel whose largest single-stage drop is the headline bottleneck; the aggregate normalizes over the dimensions actually measured.\n400: \n401: #### Current Reality\n402: \n403: `scripts/skill-benchmark/score-skill-benchmark.cjs` scores D1 inter+intra, D2 discovery, D3 efficiency, D5 connectivity, and reports D4 usefulness as `unscored` until live mode; weights live in `assets/skill-benchmark/default_profile.json`.\n404: \n405: #### Source Files\n406: \n407: `scripts/skill-benchmark/score-skill-benchmark.cjs`, `assets/skill-benchmark/default_profile.json`.\n408: \n409: ### Dual report and remediation taxonomy\n410: \n411: #### Description\n412: \n413: Emits a machine report plus a human report rendered from it (anti-drift), with ranked bottlenecks mapped to concrete remediations and hand-off lanes.\n414: \n415: #### Current Reality\n416: \n417: `scripts/skill-benchmark/build-report.cjs` renders `skill-benchmark-report.md` FROM `skill-benchmark-report.json`; bottlenecks map through `assets/skill-benchmark/remediation_taxonomy.json` to a target file, locus, one-line fix, and hand-off lane.\n418: \n419: #### Source Files\n420: \n421: `scripts/skill-benchmark/build-report.cjs`, `assets/skill-benchmark/remediation_taxonomy.json`.\n\n(End of file - total 421 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"deep-improvement: Feature Catalog\"\ndescription: \"Unified reference combining the evaluation loop, integration scanning, scoring, model-benchmark mode, and skill-benchmark mode surfaces that currently ship in deep-improvement.\"\n---\n\n# deep-improvement: Feature Catalog\n\nThis document combines the current feature inventory for the `deep-improvement` system into a single reference. The root catalog acts as the system-level directory: it summarizes the evaluation loop, the integration scanner, the deterministic scoring stack, the model-benchmark mode, and the skill-benchmark mode, then points to the per-feature files that carry the deeper implementation and validation anchors.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nUse this catalog as the canonical inventory for the live `deep-improvement` feature surface. The numbered sections below group the skill by runtime responsibility so readers can move from a top-level summary into per-feature reference files without losing the current code and operator-contract context behind each claim.\n\n### Lane Legend\n\nThe skill runs three lanes through one agent. Each category and feature below is tagged with the lane it serves.\n\n| Lane | Meaning | Entry Point |","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md","time":{"start":1780204960071,"end":1780204960093}},"id":"prt_e7c7bf7e5001qLigsAc0ywHvHg","sessionID":"ses_183846c24ffe2Qtb7Q7eSJvXlI","messageID":"msg_e7c7bda26001QLqUg47WFBhmYt"}}
